{% import "macros.njk" as m %}

<div class="calc">
  <div class="inputs">
    {{ m.field('p', 'Investment amount', '₹', 1000, 100000000, 1000, 100000, '₹1k', '₹10 Cr') }}
    {{ m.field('r', 'Expected return (p.a.)', '%', 1, 30, 0.5, 12, '1%', '30%') }}
    {{ m.field('n', 'Investment period', 'years', 1, 40, 1, 10, '1 yr', '40 yrs') }}
    <div class="result-actions"><button class="btn-ghost" data-copylink>Copy link to this calculation</button></div>
  </div>
  <div class="results">
    <div class="stat-row">
      <div class="stat hero"><div class="k">Future value</div><div class="v" id="out-fv">—</div><div class="sub" id="out-fv-sub"></div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="k">Invested</div><div class="v" id="out-inv">—</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="k">Wealth gained</div><div class="v pos" id="out-gain">—</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="k">Money multiple</div><div class="v" id="out-x">—</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="chart-box"><canvas id="chart-growth"></canvas></div>
    <p class="chart-note">Value at the end of each year.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<details class="sched">
  <summary>Year-by-year growth table</summary>
  <div id="sched-out"></div>
</details>

<article class="article">
  <h2>Compounding, visualised</h2>
  <p>A lumpsum investment is the purest demonstration of compound growth: you invest once and every year's return is earned on an ever-larger base. The curve looks flat at first and steep later — at 12%, an investment gains as much in years 13–18 as it did in its entire first 12 years. The practical lesson is that time in the market matters more than the amount: money you can leave untouched for 15–20 years does extraordinary work.</p>

  <h2>Formula</h2>
  <div class="formula">FV = P × (1 + r)<sup>t</sup></div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>P</strong> — amount invested today</li>
    <li><strong>r</strong> — expected annual return (as a decimal)</li>
    <li><strong>t</strong> — years invested</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>₹1,00,000 invested at 12% p.a. for 10 years: FV = 1,00,000 × (1.12)<sup>10</sup> ≈ <strong>₹3,10,585</strong> — your money roughly triples. Leave it another 10 years and it becomes about ₹9.65 lakh; the second decade adds more than twice what the first did, without you investing another rupee.</p>

  <h2>How to use this calculator</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Enter the amount, expected annual return and holding period.</li>
    <li>The money-multiple tile shows how many times your investment grows.</li>
    <li>Compare with the <a href="/sip-calculator/">SIP calculator</a> if you are deciding between investing at once or monthly.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<script>
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
  function recalc() {
    var p = CM.val('p'), r = CM.val('r') / 100, t = CM.val('n');
    if (p <= 0 || t <= 0) return;
    var fv = p * Math.pow(1 + r, t);

    CM.set('out-fv', CM.inr(fv));
    var w = CM.words(fv);
    CM.set('out-fv-sub', w ? 'about ' + w : '');
    CM.set('out-inv', CM.inr(p));
    CM.set('out-gain', CM.inr(fv - p));
    CM.set('out-x', CM.num(fv / p, 2) + '×');

    var labels = [], series = [], rows = [];
    for (var y = 0; y <= t; y++) {
      var v = p * Math.pow(1 + r, y);
      labels.push('Y' + y); series.push(v);
      if (y > 0) rows.push([y, CM.inr(v - p), CM.inr(v)]);
    }
    CM.lineChart('chart-growth', labels, [{ label: 'Value', data: series, role: '--s1', fill: true }]);
    CM.table('sched-out', ['Year', 'Gain', 'Value'], rows);
  }
  CM.bind(['p', 'r', 'n'], recalc);
});
</script>
